cleaned_message: I'm reflecting on the last 2.5 months of pain, surgeries, bedrest and all their consequences this morning. Many people go through far worse for far longer periods of time, but I have still taken something away from this. I thought I knew perseverance, I thought I understood what it meant to go through stress and pain and come out the other side. My family and I have been doing just that for years, after all. I didn't truly understand it spiritually, though, until I stepped back into the gym yesterday. I've tried for almost a month to make it in and work through, but I allowed myself to be interrupted each time. Yesterday, with tubes and uncomfortable equipment attached to me, I went back. I didn't do a usual workout, I only made it through about half of what I normally would do, but I still made it. Each and every lift, every press, every single time I would lie on the bench and wince for a moment, it all started to make sense. I didn't push too hard, but I pushed to my current limit, and even that was a challenge. It was painful each time (not the muscle kind that signals you to stop, I was cleared for this by a surgeon.), but when I pressed the weight above my chest and exhaled, it was like all the fear and exhaustion went out. The Holy Spirit was with me, and taught me a lesson I thought I understood; Overcoming pain, whether physical or mental, is a moment of pure joy in the glory of God. When you fall into the arms of the Father, unsure of where it will lead you, you will find where you are meant to be in Him. Take Him with you, because He IS strength. url_description: (May 11) The investigation continues now that Gregory and Travis McMichael have been booked into the Glynn County Jail in the Feb. 23 shooting of Ahmaud Arbery, and Reynolds said "every stone will be uncovered." But in response to a question about racial intent in the shooting, Georgia Bureau of Investigation Director Vic Reynolds said "there is no hate crime in Georgia. There isn't. It is one of four or five states that doesn't have one." But family attorney for Ahmaud Arbery says the situation would have been different if a white man was shot. "And so, we want the Georgia Bureau of Investigators to investigate the entire case from top to bottom. And why people did not do their jobs as if you put the shoe another foot. Why didn't we have equal justice and due process for the benefit of Ahmaud Arbery like you would have had if it was a young white man laying dead on the ground," he said Friday speaking to the Associated Press. The McMichaels told police they pursued Arbery, with another person recording them on video, after spotting him running in their neighborhood. The father and son said they thought he matched the appearance of a burglary suspect recorded on a surveillance camera. "All you have to do is watch the video and then show probable cause. And that's what we were so outraged about because the police officers on day one who saw that video should have made arrest than, but because of the relationships they had with Greg McMichaels, one of their former colleagues, a detective in the D.A.'s office and a former police officer. They either intentionally looked the other way or it was just incompetence," Crump said. Arbery's mother, Wanda Cooper Jones, has said she thinks her son, a former football player, was just jogging in the Satilla Shores neighborhood before he was killed on a Sunday afternoon. National outrage over the case swelled this week after the cellphone video was leaked and shared on social media. Hundreds gathered to protest in Brunswick, Georgia on Friday as well. Crump asked the protesters to be safe and maintain social distancing. üá¨üáßüá©üá™ How the British government killed its nascent automotive industry and allowed Germany to become the European leader in car manufacturing Regular intercity bus services by steam-powered buses were pioneered in England in the 1830s by associates of Sir Goldsworthy Gurney and by Walter Hancock among others, running reliable services over road conditions which were too hazardous for horse-drawn transportation. Steam carriages were much less likely to overturn, and did not "run away with" the customer as horses sometimes did. They travelled faster than horse-drawn carriages (24 mph or 39 km/h over four miles or 6.4 kilometres and an average of 12 mph or 19 km/h over longer distances). They could run at a half to a third of the cost of horse-drawn carriages. Their brakes did not lock and drag like horse-drawn transport (a phenomenon that increased damage to roads). According to engineers, steam carriages caused one-third the damage to the road surface as that caused by the action of horses' feet. Indeed, the wide tires of the steam carriages (designed for better traction) caused virtually no damage to the streets, whereas the narrow wheels of the horse-drawn carriages (designed to reduce the effort required of horses) tended to cause rutting. At the time, in the 1830s, England or the UK, was the only country in the world to have motor vehicles in use for road transportation and the companies that were producing them were profitable. Britain was set to become the home of the automobile in the first half of the 19th century and take over the world but that never happened. With the rise of steam-powered bus companies, accusations began appearing in the British press that the new technology, steam buses, posed a great danger to pedestrians, damaged roads, scared horses and created all sorts of risks. The media campaign was sponsored by rail and freight companies who used trains and horse-drawn stage coaches. They had much greater financial power compared to the new steam bus companies as they were much older and already established in the market. The stage coach and railway companies then lobbied the British Parliament to pass several Turnpike Acts which imposed heavy tolls on steam carriages under the false presumption that steam carriages were harmful for roads making their use simply unprofitable for the owners of the steam buses. But the lobbyists were not done. In 1861 the British Parliament passed the Locomotives Act imposing restrictive speed limits on "road locomotives" of 5 mph (8.0 km/h) in towns and cities, and 10 mph (16 km/h) in the country. In 1865, a new Locomotives Act followed which was even more restrictive. It further reduced the speed limits to 4 mph (6.4 km/h) in the country and just 2 mph (3.2 km/h) in towns and cities, additionally requiring a man bearing a red flag to precede every vehicle. At the same time, the act gave local authorities the power to specify the hours during which any such vehicle might use the roads. The companies still using steam carriages up to 1865 went bankrupt soon thereafter as the steam carriage was prohibited, by law, to use what made it superior to horse-drawn carriages thus ending what could have been the birth of the automotive industry. In 1867 Nicolaus Otto, a German engineer, unveiled at the Paris World Exhibition the compressed charge internal combustion engine which ran on petroleum gas. Although primitive, it was lighter than a steam engine, and the fact that it did not require coal to operate, made it far easier to use. It took some time before the engine was used in automobiles because German inventors had to overcome similar challenges like their British counterparts decades earlier when building steam buses due to fear of railway and freight companies losing to competition. Despite this, Karl Benz unveiled in 1885 his first vehicle, much smaller and cruder than a steam carriage. He however was free of legal restrictions from the German government and was able to develop a profitable business and the rest is history. @CIG_telegram
